<BlogPostLayout
  title="Multi-Display Magic in Android: Sending Messages to a Second Screen"
  description="Android's multi-display API is underused and underrated. Here's how to launch activities on a secondary display and communicate between them."
  canonicalUrl="https://waseemarain4u.github.io/my-portfolio/blog-article-multi-display"
  ogImage="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1527443224154-c4a3942d3acf?w=1200&q=80"
  tag="Android"
  date="Sep 5, 2023"
  readTime="6 min read"
  mediumUrl="https://medium.com/@waseemarain_98671/multi-display-magic-in-android-sending-messages-to-a-second-screen-cd8225a9f3db"
>
  <p>Most Android developers never think about secondary displays. But if you've ever worked on retail kiosks, digital signage, presentation apps, or Android Automotive, you've already needed this. Android's multi-display support has been production-ready since API 26, and the API is simpler than most people expect.</p>

  <h2>When does this matter?</h2>
  <p>The use cases are more common than they appear. A point-of-sale system where the cashier sees an order management screen and the customer faces a payment/receipt display. An Android TV app driving both a main screen and a status bar. A vehicle infotainment system where the driver and passenger see different content. All of these require launching and controlling activities on a display that isn't the primary one.</p>

  <h2>Detecting available displays</h2>
  <p>The entry point is <code>DisplayManager</code>, which you get from the system service. It gives you a list of all connected displays and lets you register a listener for display connect/disconnect events.</p>
  <pre>val displayManager = getSystemService(Context.DISPLAY_SERVICE) as DisplayManager
val displays = displayManager.displays

// Find secondary displays
val secondaryDisplays = displays.filter {"{"} it.displayId != Display.DEFAULT_DISPLAY {"}"}</pre>
  <p>Always listen for display changes at runtime — external displays can connect and disconnect at any time, and your app needs to handle both gracefully.</p>

  <h2>Launching an Activity on a specific display</h2>
  <p>Once you have the target display's ID, you create an <code>ActivityOptions</code> bundle specifying the launch display, then pass it to <code>startActivity</code>.</p>
  <pre>val options = ActivityOptions.makeBasic().apply {"{"}
    launchDisplayId = targetDisplay.displayId
{"}"}
val intent = Intent(this, SecondScreenActivity::class.java)
startActivity(intent, options.toBundle())</pre>
  <p>That's the core of it. The activity launches on the specified display as a normal Android activity, with its own lifecycle, window, and view hierarchy.</p>

  <h2>Communicating between screens</h2>
  <p>This is where it gets interesting. Since both activities run in the same process, you have several clean options for communication:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Shared ViewModel:</strong> Both activities share a ViewModel scoped to the application — state changes in one are immediately reflected in the other via LiveData or StateFlow.</li>
    <li><strong>Local Broadcast:</strong> Use <code>LocalBroadcastManager</code> to send events between activities without any cross-process overhead.</li>
    <li><strong>EventBus / shared repository:</strong> A singleton repository with a shared <code>StateFlow</code> is the cleanest architecture-friendly approach.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The shared ViewModel approach integrates most naturally with modern Android architecture. Both the primary and secondary screen activities observe the same state, and any update from either side propagates automatically.</p>

  <h2>Handling display disconnection</h2>
  <p>A secondary display can disappear at any time — the user unplugs HDMI, a Bluetooth display times out, or the device switches modes. Register a <code>DisplayManager.DisplayListener</code> and handle <code>onDisplayRemoved</code> to gracefully wind down any activities running on the disconnected display. Failing to do this results in orphaned activities and potential ANRs.</p>
  <p>Multi-display development opens up a class of app experiences that most Android developers haven't explored. The API is well-documented and surprisingly approachable — the hard part is designing the UX, not writing the code.</p>

